# Python Coding Guidelines

<!-- Edit this file directly. Committed to git and shared with the team. -->

## Style
- Follow PEP 8
- Max line length: 100 characters
- Use type hints on all public functions
- Docstrings: Google style for public APIs

## Naming
- Functions/methods: snake_case
- Classes: PascalCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Private members: _single_leading_underscore

## Imports
- Standard library first, then third-party, then local
- No wildcard imports (`from x import *`)
- Absolute imports preferred

## Functions
- Keep functions ≤ 40 lines
- Single responsibility
- Early returns over nested if/else

## Error handling
- Use specific exceptions, not bare `except`
- Never `except: pass` — at minimum `except Exception as e: logger.error(...)`
- Raise ValueError for bad inputs, RuntimeError for unexpected states

## Async
- All I/O should be async if the codebase is async
- Never mix sync and async without explicit bridging
- Use `async with` for context managers, not raw await

## Testing (pytest)
- Test files in tests/ directory, mirroring src/ structure
- Use fixtures for setup/teardown
- Mock external services, never real network calls in unit tests
- Parametrize for multiple input cases

## SQLAlchemy (if used)
- Use `async with session_maker() as session` — never raw session
- No lazy loading in async context
- Migrations via Alembic — never ALTER TABLE manually

## Logging
- Use `logging.getLogger(__name__)`
- No `print()` in production code
- Log at appropriate levels: DEBUG/INFO/WARNING/ERROR/CRITICAL
